          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>12381</commentid>
            <who name="Sebastian Werner">info</who>
            <bug_when>2009-09-17 10:17:55 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>I also think the changes are save to apply. Even when there are scripts which post-process the generated API data (e.g. for using it further) it&#39;s easy to rename it there as well.

*.json is directly supported by Aptana, but also works well in TextMate, Netbeans etc. Should not be that an issue. Also like to highlight that JSON is no valid JavaScript and this way opening it as JavaScript might produce validation errors like in Aptana. *.json is the much better extension highlighting that difference.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>12447</commentid>
            <who name="Andreas Ecker">qooxdoo</who>
            <bug_when>2009-09-21 10:53:23 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>Thomas, if you also think it&#39;s a useful albeit minor change, please review/apply Helder&#39;s proposed patch (only 0.8+). Do you know of other files that could also benefit from a more distinct file extension?</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>13087</commentid>
            <who name="Thomas Herchenroeder">thron7</who>
            <bug_when>2009-10-12 12:28:06 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>down prio; the big issue here is that we are actually *not* using Json, but 
Javascript literal notation; if we changed the file extension we should 
consequently make the contents comply with Json, part. map keys need to be 
double quoted (which would increase file size); i&#39;m not sure its&#39; worth the 
effort</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>13115</commentid>
            <who name="Sebastian Werner">info</who>
            <bug_when>2009-10-12 17:18:12 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>Ok, that&#39;s right Thomas. Still it&#39;s is also no JavaScript at the moment. I have the feeling that going the JSON way is still the right way. The size is not that relevant there IMHO. Maybe one could do the  renaming first and then modify the generated content afterwards.</thetext>
